Despite the B rated and minor grunginess apparent only on the way to the restrooms, this place offers a solid, very good tasting experience at VERY reasonable prices. IMO there are pretty much 2 categories of Sushi restaurants in the US, Japanese run Sushi, establishments that honor, pay homage and represent this true Japanese traditional art form and then those establishments seeking capitalize on America's lust for indiscrimate sushi rolls of any variety or quality that have become part of the American vernacular for take-out/delivery. To be very clear, this restaurant is NOT the former. This is no gourmet, Japanese style artfully crafted environment. With that being said, if your looking to go out for sushi and an experience moderately about the offering of your typical pan-asian sushi delivery options at an affordable yet surprisingly delicious standard, Natto is a great choice for doing so.

Top notch sush. Service? Exceptional. Experience? Unbeatable. Entertainment? In spades.  I’ve been an avid follower of Scott Matus’ reviews for a while. Worship the guy’s whole calatlog. Where he goes I follow, because he’s got an eye for quality that’s unsurpassed.  As per usual, he did not lead me astray. One filet mignon and shrimp combo later, I was in hibachi heaven. Combine that with a firehouse of sake to the face and I’ve been transported to cloud nine. Nothing better, second year in a row.  I’m a man who values value, and at Natto I was not dissapointed. It’s essentially ruined all other culinary experiences for me. Quite frankly, if a vegetable is thrown into my mouth, I’m no longer consuming it. Sorry, Mom.  5/5, two thumbs up, and one full stomach later I’m a happy camper.  Thanks enthusiastic and attentive staff of Natto. And thank you a thousand times, fellow reviewer Scott Matus. You’re my North Star, my shining light, my Buddha-bellied mentor and I, as always, will follow you to the ends of the earth.
